    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1957-12-18T04:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1957-12-18T04:30:00-05:00" n="373"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d373">
                <head>373. Memorandum of a Conversation, Ambassador’s Residence, Paris, December 18,
                    1957, 10:30 a.m.<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d373fn1">Source: Department of
                        State, President’s Memoranda of Conversation: Lot 66 D 149, 1956–1959.
                        Secret. Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_RSW1">Rockwell</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <gloss target="#t_USDel1">USDel</gloss>/MC/33</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" type="conversation-or-meeting-date"
                            when="1957-12-18T10:30:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 18, 1957, 10:30 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>
                        <hi rend="italic">United States</hi>
                        <list>
                            <item>The President</item>
                            <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_RSW1">Rockwell</persName>
                            </item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <hi rend="italic">Turkey</hi>
                        <list>
                            <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MA1">Adnan Menderes</persName>, Prime
                                Minister of Turkey</item>
                            <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_ZFR1">Fatin Zorlu</persName>, Foreign
                                Minister of Turkey</item>
                            <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_EM1">Melih Esenbel</persName>, Secretary
                                General of the Turkish Foreign Office</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Egypt</item>
                </list>
                <p>Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_MA1">Menderes</persName> said that we must
                    not accept a fait accompli in Syria. The President thought that there might be
                    some possibility of hopeful developments there. He knew how staunchly Turkey had
                    opposed the Communist penetration of Syria. Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MA1"
                        >Menderes</persName> said that Turkey was gratified by the way the United
                    States had stood by Turkey. The USSR had not failed to notice this.</p>
                <p>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MA1">Menderes</persName> commented that <persName
                        corresp="#p_NBM1">Nuri</persName> Said had just been in Turkey and had said
                    that his recent talks with the President and the Secretary in Washington<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d373fn2">On December 5 and 10, <persName corresp="#p_NBM1"
                            >Nuri</persName> discussed the Arab-Israeli conflict and related matters
                        with <persName>Dulles</persName> in Washington.</note> about Syria had been
                    most satisfactory.</p>
                <p>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MA1">Menderes</persName> said that Turkey had no
                    illusion about <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss>’s abilities to be helpful
                    in the Middle East. <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> was divided, but US
                    policy must continue strong in the Middle East.</p>
                <p>The President asked what Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MA1">Menderes</persName>
                    thought of the military situation in Syria. The Prime Minister said that the
                    Russians have sent Syria more arms than Syria can use. The Soviets have not made
                    Syria into a Communist satellite yet, because they are afraid of public reaction
                    in the Arab world. They have put their hand on Syria, however, and can come in
                    at any time.</p>
            </div>
